"“Tasmātihānanda, eseva hetu etaṃ nidānaṃ esa samudayo esa paccayo phassassa, "
"yadidaṃ nāmarūpaṃ."
msgstr ""
"“That’s why this is the cause, source, origin, and condition of contact, "
"namely mental and physical phenomena."

#. </p><p><a class="sc" id="29"></a><a class="wp" id="21"></a><a class="pts"
#. id="pts2.63"></a>
msgctxt "dn15:32.1"
msgid ""
"‘Viññāṇapaccayā nāmarūpan’ti iti kho panetaṃ vuttaṃ, tadānanda, imināpetaṃ "
"pariyāyena veditabbaṃ, yathā viññāṇapaccayā nāmarūpaṃ."
msgstr ""
"‘Consciousness is a condition for mental and physical phemomena’—that’s what "
"I said. And this is a way to understand how this is so."

# samuccissatha, to be read samucchissatha is the same as muccati/mucchati found at Dhp#71. (See Norman's note in his Dhp translation.) There it refers to the curdling of milk. It is important to keep this metaphor intact, and in ancient times it was commonly believed that conception happened with the coagulation of the menstrual blood and semen. Whether this is literally implied in the current passage is not the point; it is clearly the metaphorical origin of the term.
msgctxt "dn15:32.2"
msgid ""
"Viññāṇañca hi, ānanda, mātukucchismiṃ na okkamissatha, api nu kho nāmarūpaṃ "
"mātukucchismiṃ samuccissathā”ti?"
msgstr ""
"If consciousness was not conceived in the mother’s womb, would mental and "
"physical phenomena coagulate there?”"

msgctxt "dn15:32.3"
msgid "“No hetaṃ, bhante”."
msgstr "“No, sir.”"

msgctxt "dn15:32.4"
msgid ""
"“Viññāṇañca hi, ānanda, mātukucchismiṃ okkamitvā vokkamissatha, api nu kho "
"nāmarūpaṃ itthattāya abhinibbattissathā”ti?"
msgstr ""
"“If consciousness, after being conceived in the mother’s womb, was to be "
"miscarried, would mental and physical phenomena be born into this state of "
"existence?”"

msgctxt "dn15:32.5"
msgid "“No hetaṃ, bhante”."
msgstr "“No, sir.”"

msgctxt "dn15:32.6"
msgid ""
"“Viññāṇañca hi, ānanda, daharasseva sato vocchijjissatha kumārakassa vā "
"kumārikāya vā, api nu kho nāmarūpaṃ vuddhiṃ virūḷhiṃ vepullaṃ "
"āpajjissathā”ti?"
msgstr ""
"“If the consciousness of a young boy or girl was to be cut off, would mental "
"and physical phenomena achieve growth, increase, and maturity?”"

msgctxt "dn15:32.7"
msgid "“No hetaṃ, bhante”."
msgstr "“No, sir.”"

msgctxt "dn15:32.8"
msgid ""
"“Tasmātihānanda, eseva hetu etaṃ nidānaṃ esa samudayo esa paccayo "
"nāmarūpassa—"
msgstr ""
"“That’s why this is the cause, source, origin, and condition of mental and "
"physical phenomena, namely consciousness."

#, fuzzy
msgctxt "dn15:32.9"
msgid "yadidaṃ viññāṇaṃ."
msgstr " "

#. </p><p><a class="sc" id="30"></a><a class="wp" id="wp22"></a><a class="pts"
#. id="pts2.64"></a>
msgctxt "dn15:33.1"
msgid ""
"‘Nāmarūpapaccayā viññāṇan’ti iti kho panetaṃ vuttaṃ, tadānanda, imināpetaṃ "
"pariyāyena veditabbaṃ, yathā nāmarūpapaccayā viññāṇaṃ."
msgstr ""
"‘Mental and physical phenomena are a condition for consiousness’—that’s what "
"I said. And this is a way to understand how this is so."

# The question here is how the synonyms samudaya and sambhava are to be treated. This phrase only occurs elsewhere at MN 138, where we have "āyatiṃ jātijarāmaraṇadukkhasamudayasambhavo na hoti". There, in his later rendering, BB has "origination of suffering—of birth, ageing, and death in the future". Thus he maintains a rendering that essentially collapses the synonyms. RD has "be manifested that concatenation of birth, old age, death and the uprising of Ill". MW has "an arising and coming to be". Thanissaro has "coming-into-play of the origination". Now, dukkhasamudaya occurs a couple hundred times elsewhere, invariably in the sense "origin of suffering". I think we should take it here in the same sense, which would agree with the syntax of RD's rendering. Comm has "Dukkhasamudayasambhavoti dukkharāsisambhavo", which at least suggests that dukkhasamudaya is to some degree separate from the rest. At MN 138 it is "Jātijarāmaraṇadukkhasamudayasambhavoti jātijarāmaraṇassa ceva avasesassa ca dukkhassa nibbatti na hotīti attho". Here, nibbatti applies equally to jati, etc. and dukkha. Also, among the PTS vll. we have "dukkhasamudayo sambhavo".
msgctxt "dn15:33.2"
msgid ""
"Viññāṇañca hi, ānanda, nāmarūpe patiṭṭhaṃ na labhissatha, api nu kho āyatiṃ "
"jātijarāmaraṇaṃ dukkhasamudayasambhavo paññāyethā”ti?"
msgstr ""
"If consciousness was not to become established in mental and physical "
"phenomena, would the coming to be of the origin of suffering—of rebirth, old "
"age, and death in the future—be found?”"

msgctxt "dn15:33.3"
msgid "“No hetaṃ, bhante”."
msgstr "“No, sir.”"

msgctxt "dn15:33.4"
msgid ""
"“Tasmātihānanda, eseva hetu etaṃ nidānaṃ esa samudayo esa paccayo viññāṇassa "
"yadidaṃ nāmarūpaṃ."
msgstr ""
"“That’s why this is the cause, source, origin, and condition of "
"consciousness, namely mental and physical phenomena."

#. VAR: jīyetha → jiyyetha (mr)
#. VAR: mīyetha → miyyetha (mr)
msgctxt "dn15:33.5"
msgid ""
"Ettāvatā kho, ānanda, jāyetha vā jīyetha vā mīyetha vā cavetha vā "
"upapajjetha vā."
msgstr ""
"This is the extent to which one may be reborn, grow old, die, pass away, or "
"reappear."

# ettāvatā vaṭṭaṃ vattati itthattaṃ paññāpanāya is tricky. Thanissaro has "the extent to which the cycle revolves for the manifesting (discernibility) of this world". This is tempting, but elsewhere pannapanaya is as expected governed by the genitive in such constructions, eg rūpakkhandhassa paññāpanāya. BB here follows comm "namapannati". But this phrase must surely be translated with eg SN 22.56 "Ye kevalino vaṭṭaṃ tesaṃ natthi paññāpanāya." "For consummate ones, there is no cycle of rebirths to be found." There BB has "there is no round for describing them". At MN 22 he has "there is no [future] round for manifestation". By his comment on SN 22.56 he is more or less agnostic on these readings. In DN 15 he has "the round turns for describing this state of being". But I find all these renderings borderline incomprehensible. 
# 
# aññamaññapaccayatā pavattati. is inserted from Comm.
msgctxt "dn15:33.6"
msgid ""
"Ettāvatā adhivacanapatho, ettāvatā niruttipatho, ettāvatā paññattipatho, "
"ettāvatā paññāvacaraṃ, ettāvatā vaṭṭaṃ vattati itthattaṃ paññāpanāya yadidaṃ "
"nāmarūpaṃ saha viññāṇena aññamaññapaccayatā pavattati."
msgstr ""
"This is how far the scope of language, terminology, and description extends; "
"how far the sphere of wisdom extends; how far the cycle of rebirths "
"continues so that this state of existence is to be found; namely, mental and "
"physical phenomena together with consciousness."

#. </p><h2>
msgctxt "dn15:34.1"
msgid "2. Attapaññatti"
msgstr "Describing the Self"

#. </h2><p><a class="sc" id="31"></a><a class="wp" id="wp23"></a>
msgctxt "dn15:35.1"
msgid "Kittāvatā ca, ānanda, attānaṃ paññapento paññapeti?"
msgstr "How do those who describe the self describe it?"

msgctxt "dn15:35.2"
msgid "Rūpiṃ vā hi, ānanda, parittaṃ attānaṃ paññapento paññapeti:"
msgstr "They describe it as physical and limited:"

msgctxt "dn15:35.3"
msgid "‘rūpī me paritto attā’ti."
msgstr "‘My self is physical and limited.’"

msgctxt "dn15:35.4"
msgid "Rūpiṃ vā hi, ānanda, anantaṃ attānaṃ paññapento paññapeti:"
msgstr "Or they describe it as physical and infinite:"

msgctxt "dn15:35.5"
msgid "‘rūpī me ananto attā’ti."
msgstr "‘My self is physical and infinite.’"

msgctxt "dn15:35.6"
msgid "Arūpiṃ vā hi, ānanda, parittaṃ attānaṃ paññapento paññapeti:"
msgstr "Or they describe it as formless and limited:"

msgctxt "dn15:35.7"
msgid "‘arūpī me paritto attā’ti."
msgstr "‘My self is formless and limited.’"

msgctxt "dn15:35.8"
msgid "Arūpiṃ vā hi, ānanda, anantaṃ attānaṃ paññapento paññapeti:"
msgstr "Or they describe it as formless and infinite:"

msgctxt "dn15:35.9"
msgid "‘arūpī me ananto attā’ti."
msgstr "‘My self is formless and infinite.’"

#. </p><p><a class="sc" id="32"></a><a class="wp" id="wp24"></a>
#. VAR: rūpiṃ → rūpī (mr)
msgctxt "dn15:36.1"
msgid "Tatrānanda, yo so rūpiṃ parittaṃ attānaṃ paññapento paññapeti."
msgstr "Now, take those who describe the self as physical and limited."

msgctxt "dn15:36.2"
msgid ""
"Etarahi vā so rūpiṃ parittaṃ attānaṃ paññapento paññapeti, tattha bhāviṃ vā "
"so rūpiṃ parittaṃ attānaṃ paññapento paññapeti, ‘atathaṃ vā pana santaṃ "
"tathattāya upakappessāmī’ti iti vā panassa hoti."
msgstr ""
"They describe the self as physical and limited in the present; or in some "
"future life; or else they think: ‘Though it is not like that, I will ensure "
"it is provided with what it needs to become like that.’"

msgctxt "dn15:36.3"
msgid ""
"Evaṃ santaṃ kho, ānanda, rūpiṃ parittattānudiṭṭhi anusetīti iccālaṃ vacanāya."
msgstr ""
"This being so, it’s appropriate to say that a view of self as physical and "
"limited underlies them."

